Expt_1 (TVE15CS021)
===================

Linux Basic Commands and Directory Operations
---------------------------------------------------------
1. touch <file name> 		# Creates a file 
2. mkdir <folder name> 		# Creates a folder
3. pwd 				# Gives the present Working directory
4. ls 				# List all files in the current directory
5. ls -l 			# Prevides a long listing of all the files
6. ls -l -h 			# Same as the above command but the file sizes will be in human readable form
7. ls -F 			# Marks all the executable with a * and all the directories with a /
8. ls --color 			# Shows a coloured listing of all the files
9.ls -a 			# Shows all the files in the present directory including the special dot files
10.cd <dirname> 		# Changes the directory to the subdirectory of the current directory
11.cd .. 			# Changes the directory to the parent directory of the current directory
12.cd ~ 			# Changes the directory to the home directory of the current user
13.cd / 			# Changes the directory to the root directory of the current user
14.cd ~<username>		# Changes the directory to the home sirectory of a different user
15.cat <filename> 		# Displays the text scroll off the screen
16.cat <file1> <file2> 		# Concatenates the contents of the two text files
17.more <filename> 		# Displays the file one scornful at a time
18.less <filename> 		# Similat but faster than the more command
19.cp <file1> <file2> 		# Copies file 1 to file 2
20.cp <file1> <dirname> 	# Copies file1 to Directory <dirname>
21.cp -r <dirname1> <dirname2> 	# Copies dirname1 directory to directory dirname2
22.mv <oldname> <newname> 	# Renames file with old name to new name
23.mv <olddir> <newdir> 	# Renames directory with name olddir to newdir
24.mv <filename> <dirname> 	# Moves files with name as filename to directory dirname
25.clear 			# Clears the terminal screen
26.locate <filename> 		# Searches for a specified filename
27.passwd 			# Prompt to change the password of the current user
28.whoami 			# Displays the details of the current logged in user
29.which <package>		# Gives the location of symbolic link of current package
30.man <commandname> 		# Finds out what a command does
31.man -f <commandname> 	# One line summary of what the command does
32.man -k <keyword> 		# Searches for a command with a particular keyword

Basic Outline of Directories in a typical Linux System
--------------------------------------------------------
1. /bin		# User Binaries
2. /sbin	# System Binaries
3. /etc		# Configuration Files
4  /dev		# Device Files
5. /proc	# Process info
6. /var		# Varibale Files	
7. /tmp		# Temporary Files
8. /usr		# User programs
9. /home	# Home Directories
10./boot	# Boot Loader Files
11./lib		# System Libs
12./opt		# Optional Add ons
13./mnt		# Mount directory
14./media	# Removable devices
15./srv		# Service Data

Executing a Bash Script
------------------------
1. cd to the directory which contains the file to be executed
2. Type "chmod +x <fileName>" which provides system permissions for the file to be executed
3. Type ./filename.sh to execute the file
